<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-258-161  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 258 161.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Jan 9 1989 v8 n1 p85(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>10Net's Tempest LAN sparks Air Force interest. (Local AreaNetwork)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Masud, S.A.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   10net Communications (products).andO;Topic:     United States. Air ForceLocal Area NetworksStandardsFiber OpticsSecurityCommunications Tapping.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>10Net's Tempest LAN Sparks Air Force InterestandM;A new Tempest-certified 10-megabit/sec fiber-optic local area network from10Net Communications apparently has caught the interest of the Air Force.andM;The recently introduced product is a Tempest version of the Marietta, Ga.,andO;company's 10Net 10-megabit/sec fiber-optic LAN.andP;  10Net officials noted thatthe Tempest configuration of their 1-megabit/sec fiber-optic LAN already isinstalled at Air Force bases worldwide by the Air Force Electronics SecurityCommand and also at FBI field offices around the country.andM;The product also has received a quick endorsement from a supplier of theslower Tempest LAN to the Air Force.andP;  &quot;We've presented the product to theElectronics Security Command at their request.andP;  They are anticipating addingthat to their overall project,&quot; said William Toten, chief executive officerof Quality Tempest Products Inc., a Herndon, Va., systems integrator.andM;&quot;They see the 10-megabit/sec as a significant improvement and are lookingforward to putting it alongside their 1-megabit/sec installations,&quot; Totenadded.andP;  He refused to provide more details.andM;10Net officials said McLean, Va., systems integrator Iverson Technology Corp.andO;supplied the 1-megabit/sec version to the FBI.andM;Ethernet InterfaceandM;An Ethernet interface card that includes a transceiver allows for directconnection to the optical fiber cable with personal computers linked in astar topology to a hub.andP;  Hub-to-hub connections allow the linking of as manyas 392 PCs, with repeaters permitting even larger configurations, 10Netofficials said.andM;Greg Goodall, president of 10Net, which is a division of DigitalCommunications Associates Inc. of Alpharetta, Ga., said the company hasdeveloped a repeater that not only allows for larger networks but also letsan Ethernet LAN connect to the fiber-optic LAN.andP;  A Tempest version of therepeater is forthcoming, he said.andM;Goodall expects the Tempest version of the 10-megabit/sec LAN to find a homein government agencies quickly.andP;  &quot;It is one of the few, if not the only,low-cost bundled fiber-optic LOANs on the market, and by the very nature ofthe technology it addresses the security needs of the government,&quot; he said.andM;The product is available immediately at an end-user price of $1,295, whichincludes the network interface card and software.andO;</TEXT></DOC>